                                    Exception],
                           tags: [ReadIOEffect, WriteIOEffect].}
returns a Stream with CSV like data as a table of header keys vs. seq[string] values, where idx 0 corresponds to the first data value The header field can be used to designate the symbol used to differentiate the header. By default #. colNames can be used to provide custom names for the columns. If any are given and a header is present with a character indiciating the header, it is automatically skipped. However, if custom names are desired and there is a real header without any starting symbol (i.e. header.len == 0), please use skipLines = N to skip it manually!   Source   Edit 
proc readCsvTyped(fname: string; sep: char = ','; header: string = "";
                  skipLines = 0; toSkip: set[char] = {}): DataFrame {...}{.
    raises: [IOError, OSError, ValueError, ValueError, ValueError], tags: [].}

Reads a DF from a CSV file using the separator character sep.

toSkip can be used to skip optional characters that may be present in the data. For instance if a CSV file is separated by ,, but contains additional whitespace (5, 10, 8 instead of 5,10,8) this can be parsed correctly by setting toSkip = {' '}.

header designates the symbol that defines the header of the CSV file. By default it's empty meaning that the first line will be treated as the header. If a header is given, e.g. "#", this means we will determine the column names from the first line (which has to start with #) and skip every line until the first line starting without #.

skipLines is used to skip N number of lines at the beginning of the file.
